06002nam a22008895i 9780812294118DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)992454587  a97808122941187 a10.9783/97808122941182doi  a(DE-B1597)481200  a(OCoLC)987755222  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN1993.5.G3 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a791.4309432231 aKillen, Andreas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomo Cinematicus :bScience, Motion Pictures, and the Making of Modern Germany /cAndreas Killen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b22 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntellectual History of the Modern Age00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. Human Science and Cinema in Germany After the Great War -- tChapter 1. Cinema and the Visual Culture of the Human Sciences -- tChapter 2. Film Reform, Mental Hygiene, and the Campaign Against “Trash,” 1912–34 -- tChapter 3. Hypnosis, Cinema, and Censorship in Germany, 1895–1933 -- tChapter 4. What Is an Enlightenment Film? Cinema and Sexual Hygiene in Interwar Germany -- tChapter 5. Scientific Cinema Between Enlightenment and Superstition, 1918–41 -- tConclusion. Science, Cinema, and the Malice of Objects -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early decades of the twentieth century, two intertwined changes began to shape the direction of German society. The baptism of the German film industry took place amid post-World War I conditions of political and social breakdown, and the cultural vacuum left by collapsing institutions was partially filled by moving images. At the same time, the emerging human sciences—psychiatry, neurology, sexology, eugenics, industrial psychology, and psychoanalysis—began to play an increasingly significant role in setting the terms for the way Germany analyzed itself and the problems it had inherited from its authoritarian past, the modernizing process, and war. Moreover, in advancing their professional and social goals, these sciences became heavily reliant on motion pictures.Situated at the intersection of film studies, the history of science and medicine, and the history of modern Germany, Homo Cinematicus connects the rise of cinema as a social institution to an inquiry into the history of knowledge production in the human sciences. Taking its title from a term coined in 1919 by commentator Wilhelm Stapel to identify a new social type that had been created by the emergence of cinema, Killen's book explores how a new class of experts in these new disciplines converged on the figure of the "homo cinematicus" and made him central to many of that era's major narratives and social policy initiatives.Killen traces film's use by the human sciences as a tool for producing, communicating, and popularizing new kinds of knowledge, as well as the ways that this alliance was challenged by popular films that interrogated the truth claims of both modern science and scientific cinema. In doing so, Homo Cinematicus endeavors to move beyond the divide between scientific and popular film, examining their historical coexistence and coevolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aCinematographyxScientific applicationszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and motion pictureszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial changezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial scienceszGermanyxHistoryy20th century.